My Pipeline Command: 

ls -A | wc -l

Explanation:

The first part ls -A, is found in man ls, and what it does is list all of the directories and subdirectories, 
however ignoring . and .., which are the current directory and parent directory. So this abides by the instructions,

Next the pipeline syntax | means we take the input of what comes first, and applies this to the command that follows.

The command that follows is found in man wc, and what it does is gets the word count, and the -l signifies
that we want the number of lines. 

This should accomplish our task of getting a count of all directories and subdirectories ignonring our
current and parent directory. 






